Visualize the accuracy for each congruency

Se her!!

Vi laver en standard joint simon task. To personer sidder ved en computer, n skal reagere nr den cirkel der dukker op p skrmen er bl, den anden nr cirklen er gul. Ved incongruent trials har cirklen vret i modsatte side af, hvor forsgspersonen der skal trykke sidder (Personen sidder f.eks. til hjre, og cirklen dukker op i venstre side af skrmen). Congruent trials har cirklen og personen i samme side. Vi har desuden samlet data om hvor ttte forsgsdeltagerne fler de er p hinanden. 1 vrende ikke srlig ttte, og 7 vrende meget ttte. I alt er der 2 independdent variabler:

congruency = cirklens position, factor

IOS = Personernes tthed, ordinal factor

og n dependent:

rt = reaktionstid i sekunder, kontunierlig skala

Testing hypothesis

Assumptions for anova

Outliers

d %>% 
  select(congruency, rt) %>% 
  group_by(congruency) %>%
  identify_outliers(rt)

5 outliers are found, but as they are not extreme (and we also already removed +-3SD) we will leave them in

Normality

# Build the linear model
model  <- lm(rt ~ IOS * congruency, d)
# Create a QQ plot of residuals
ggqqplot(residuals(model))

Looks okay.

# Compute Shapiro-Wilk test of normality
shapiro_test(residuals(model))
## # A tibble: 1 x 3
##   variable         statistic  p.value
##   <chr>                <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 residuals(model)     0.982 0.000372

P-value of 0.0003 means that it is statisticly different than a normal distribution :(

Transform data and try again

d$log_rt <- log(d$rt)
# Build the linear model
model  <- lm(log_rt ~ IOS * congruency, d)
# Create a QQ plot of residuals
ggqqplot(residuals(model))

# Compute Shapiro-Wilk test of normality
shapiro_test(residuals(model))
## # A tibble: 1 x 3
##   variable         statistic p.value
##   <chr>                <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1 residuals(model)     0.995   0.329

Allright! well take the log tranformation

Alternatives to normal anova

# Kruskal-Wallis anova (for non-normal data) - does not work, can only take one independent variable :'(

# kruskal.test(log_rt ~ IOS * congruency, d)

what dooo??? (Should we just do the normal anova? Cause that is what we would do if we had enough data probably. It is hella sus that it is significant, it doesnt look like that when looking at the barplots with errorbars)

Do we even have a simon effect?

Assumptions

Outlier assumption

d %>% 
  select(congruency, log_rt) %>% 
  group_by(congruency) %>%
  identify_outliers(log_rt)
## [1] congruency log_rt     is.outlier is.extreme
## <0 rows> (or 0-length row.names)

One, not-extreme outlier is ok.

Normality assumption

# Build the linear model
model  <- lm(log_rt ~ congruency, d)
# Create a QQ plot of residuals
ggqqplot(residuals(model))

# Compute Shapiro-Wilk test of normality
shapiro_test(residuals(model))
## # A tibble: 1 x 3
##   variable         statistic   p.value
##   <chr>                <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 residuals(model)     0.976 0.0000311

Data is closer to (but isnt) normal with log transformation, so lets use the Kruskal-Wallis anova. (that also doesnt have the assumption of homogneity of variance)

Anova

#Kruskal-Wallis anova, that is okay with non-normal data:
kruskal.test(rt ~ congruency, d)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  rt by congruency
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 15.431, df = 1, p-value = 8.557e-05

yay! at least we see the simon effect. WAIT THIS SHOULD JUST BE A TETESTSTETTS
